Otto Skorzeny made a design for a manned V1 rocket where the pilot was able to parachute out of the aircraft before impact. He said he disliked how the Japanese kamikaze meant certain death, his idea was that the agent/pilot should always have at least a small chance of survival.

In any special commando operation he planned, he made sure the participants (and enemies) should at least theoretically be able to make it out alive, even if unlikely. This is still an "active" topic, e.g. with Prigozhin saying an infantryman who dies in action "has done his job"

His tactic of just walking up calmly unarmed towards guards, enemy soldiers, security, etc. who are too surprised to shoot on sight was used by a few Russian soldiers that walked up to an Ukrainian patrol but they shot the guy instead of just disarming him which was askorzenian
